description: When to plan, how to spec, validate assumptions — Plan mode, definition of done, incremental delivery
alwaysApply: true
---

# Think before coding

- **Small / obvious** (typo, one-liner, follow existing pattern): implement directly.
- **Large or ambiguous** (new feature, multi-file, unclear requirements, meaningful trade-offs): slow down — clarify goals, constraints, and **acceptance criteria** first.

# Planning and Plan mode

- Use **Plan mode** (or an explicit written plan) when work spans multiple files, systems, or milestones, or when direction is still open.
- Good plans name: **goal**, **context** (what files/errors matter), **constraints**, and **done when** (what verifies success — tests, commands, UX checks). Save substantial plans under `.cursor/plans/` when you want resumable team context ([Cursor agent best practices](https://cursor.com/blog/agent-best-practices)).
- If implementation diverges from intent, **revise the plan** (or revert and re-run) rather than stacking corrective prompts.

# Validate risky assumptions

- Before large changes to **prompts**, **AI integrations**, **regex/parsers**, **schemas**, **migrations**, or **external APIs**: gather evidence — grep usages, reproduce in a test or script, or hit the real endpoint/stage when safe.

# Spec shape

- “Spec” = whatever fits: bullet plan, phased checklist, short ADR — not a mandatory repo folder.
- After planning, implement in **increments** with verification between steps when that reduces risk.

# Depth

- Do not replace product judgment: when the user’s goals conflict with a generic template, ask or propose options.
